<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="41">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">New to Sweden.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ach" authorityYear="1810" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Nephromataceae" genus="Nephroma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Nephroma helveticum" order="Peltigerales" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="helveticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">Nephroma helveticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a cosmopolitan species complex with a wide ecological amplitude and a large morphological and chemical 
<pageBreakToken pageId="9" pageNumber="42" start="start">variation</pageBreakToken>
. In Europe, however, the species is very rare and appears to have declined considerably (Klepsland 2103, 
<bibRefCitation author="James, PW" journalOrPublisher="Lichenologist" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="215 - 268" publicationUrl="10.1017/S0024282987000239" refId="B36" refString="James, PW, White, FJ, 1987. Studies on the genus Nephroma I. The European and Macaronesian species. Lichenologist 19: 215 - 268, DOI: 10.1017/S0024282987000239" title="Studies on the genus Nephroma I. The European and Macaronesian species." url="10.1017/S0024282987000239" volume="19" year="1987">James and White 1987</bibRefCitation>
). There are very few recent finds, among them a locality in Oppland in Norway, which is the first find in that country (
<bibRefCitation author="Klepsland, J" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="33 - 38" refId="B38" refString="Klepsland, J, 2013. Nephroma helveticum and N. tangeriense new to Norway. Graphis Scripta 25: 33 - 38" title="Nephroma helveticum and N. tangeriense new to Norway." volume="25" year="2013">Klepsland 2013</bibRefCitation>
). In the Nordic countries it is elsewhere known from a few old localities in Finland (
<bibRefCitation author="Vitikainen, O" journalOrPublisher="Nordic Lichen Flora" pageId="25" pageNumber="58" pagination="91 - 95" refId="B68" refString="Vitikainen, O, 2007. Nephromataceae. Nordic Lichen Flora 3: 91 - 95" title="Nephromataceae." volume="3" year="2007">Vitikainen 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Here we report it from one locality found in 2009 in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Västerbotten">Vaesterbotten</normalizedToken>
and in addition we have found an old specimen in the herbarium in Stockholm from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Västerbotten">Vaesterbotten</normalizedToken>
collected by Sten Ahlner in 1945 but never reported in the literature. The two localities are located 2.5 kilometers apart. We also report a second find of this species in Norway. The species is recognized by its tomentose lower surface without papillae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Nephroma helveticum (O L- 196491) Scale: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64932" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">7</figureCitation>
) and its chemistry of secondary metabolites, including the terpenoid T4 (
<bibRefCitation author="James, PW" journalOrPublisher="Lichenologist" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="215 - 268" publicationUrl="10.1017/S0024282987000239" refId="B36" refString="James, PW, White, FJ, 1987. Studies on the genus Nephroma I. The European and Macaronesian species. Lichenologist 19: 215 - 268, DOI: 10.1017/S0024282987000239" title="Studies on the genus Nephroma I. The European and Macaronesian species." url="10.1017/S0024282987000239" volume="19" year="1987">James and White 1987</bibRefCitation>
). The most similar species 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. resupinatum" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="resupinatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">N. resupinatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has a tomentose lower surface but has white papillae between the tomentum and lacks secondary metabolites. One of the recently collected specimen from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Västerbotten">Vaesterbotten</normalizedToken>
has been barcoded and the ITS sequence confirms the identity as 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. helveticum" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="helveticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">N. helveticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973740" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64932" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" start="Figure 7" startId="F7">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Figure 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ach" authorityYear="1810" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Nephromataceae" genus="Nephroma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Nephroma helveticum" order="Peltigerales" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="helveticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Nephroma helveticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(O L-196491) Scale: 5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="42">
On 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ahlner´s">Ahlner's</normalizedToken>
locality, Borstaberget, the bedrock consists of greenstone (porphyrite) and the mountain has long southwest facing slopes with steep cliffs. Ahlner collected, together with 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. helveticum" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="helveticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">N. helveticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also the rare lichen 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Physciaceae" genus="Heterodermia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Heterodermia speciosa" order="Lecanorales" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="speciosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Heterodermia speciosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. On the mountain Mitti-Skansberget 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. helveticum" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="helveticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">N. helveticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in 2009 in two places 200 meters apart. It was found growing on conglomerate cliffs in the southwest facing precipices. Other species that were found on the cliffs were 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Peltigeraceae" genus="Peltigera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Peltigera rufescens" order="Lecanorales" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Peltigera rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Lobariaceae" genus="Lobaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Lobaria scrobiculata" order="Peltigerales" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="scrobiculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Lobaria scrobiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. pulmonaria" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="pulmonaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">L. pulmonaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Pannariaceae" genus="Fuscopannaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Fuscopannaria leucophaea" order="Lecanorales" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="leucophaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Fuscopannaria leucophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Biatora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Biatora vernalis" order="Lecanorales" pageId="9" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="vernalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="42">Biatora vernalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
